content:
Here’s a tiny, self‑contained webpage that will show a random joke each time the button is pressed.  
All you need is a single HTML file – copy the code below, save it as `index.html`, and open it in a browser.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>Random Joke Generator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background: #f0f0f0;
        }
        #joke {
            margin-top: 20px;
            padding: 1em;
            width: 80%;
            max-width: 500px;
            background: white;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            border-radius: 8px;
            font-size: 1.2em;
            text-align: center;
            box-shadow: 0 2px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Press the button for a random joke!</h1>
    <button id="pickBtn">Tell me a joke!</button>
    <div id="joke"></div>

    <script>
        const jokes = [
            "Why don’t scientists trust atoms? Because they make up everything!",
            "I told my wife she was drawing her eyebrows too high. She looked surprised.",
            "Why was the math book sad? Because it had too many problems.",
            "What did the ocean say to the beach? Nothing – it just waved."
        ];

        document.getElementById('pickBtn').addEventListener('click', () => {
            // Pick a random joke
            const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length);
            document.getElementById('joke').textContent = jokes[randomIndex];
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**How it works**

1. The page contains a button (`#pickBtn`) and an empty `<div>` (`#joke`).
2. When the button is clicked, the script selects a random index from the `jokes` array using `Math.random()` and `Math.floor()`.
3. The chosen joke is then displayed inside the `#joke` div.

Save the file and open it in any browser – you’ll see a new joke each time you press the button. Enjoy!

Here’s how you can make the joke text appear in red – just give the element that shows the joke a CSS rule that sets its text color to red.  
If you’re sticking with the single‑page example from the previous reply, just add a selector that targets the element that holds the joke (in that snippet it’s the `<div id="joke">`).  

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Random Joke</title>
  <style>
    /* 1️⃣   Target the element that displays the joke  */
    #joke {
      color: red;          /* text color set to red */
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      font-size: 1.2rem;
      margin-top: 1rem;
    }
  </style>
</head>

<body>
  <h1>Random Joke</h1>

  <!-- button to trigger a new joke -->
  <button id="newJokeBtn">Tell me a joke!</button>

  <!-- the element that receives the joke text -->
  <div id="joke"></div>

  <script>
    // ---- The original joke‑generator code ----
    const jokes = [
      "Why don’t programmers like nature? Too many bugs.",
      "Why do Java developers wear glasses? Because they can’t C#.",
      "Why did the scarecrow win an award? Because he was outstanding in his field.",
      "Why did the chicken cross the road? To get to the other side of the API."
    ];

    // Grab the button and the joke‑display element
    const button = document.getElementById('newJokeBtn');
    const jokeDiv = document.getElementById('joke');

    // Function that picks a random joke and displays it
    function showRandomJoke() {
      const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length);
      jokeDiv.textContent = jokes[randomIndex];
    }

    // Click handler
    button.addEventListener('click', showRandomJoke);
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How it works

1. **CSS rule**  
   ```css
   #joke { color: red; }
   ```
   - `#joke` – targets the `<div>` with `id="joke"`.  
   - `color: red;` – changes the text color to red.

2. **HTML** – the same `<div id="joke"></div>` will now render its content (the joke) in red.

3. **Flexibility**  
   If you prefer to style multiple joke elements or use classes instead of an ID, replace `#joke` with a class selector:

   ```css
   .joke { color: red; }
   ```
   and add `class="joke"` to any element that should be red.

### Bonus: Change the color via JavaScript

If you want to switch between colors on the fly, you can also add a class dynamically:

```js
jokeDiv.classList.toggle('red');   // toggle
```

```css
.red { color: red; }
```

That way you can add or remove the `.red` class with JavaScript instead of a static CSS rule.  

That’s all you need: just add the `color: red;` style for the element that contains the joke. Happy coding!
